<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-10-06T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-10-06T00:00:00-05:00" n="1274" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1274">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72116/79</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the President of the American Institute of Architects</hi>
                                (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">R. Clipston
                                Sturgis</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <dateline>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-10-06">
                                <hi rend="italic">October 6, 1914</hi>.</date>
                        </dateline>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The Secretary of State directs me to
                            acknowledge the receipt, by reference from the <persName corresp="#p_WS1">White House</persName>, of your letter of September
                            24 protesting against the alleged destruction of architectural monuments
                            in Europe, and in reply to inform you that your remarks have received
                            the attention of the Department.<note n="2" xml:id="d1274fn1">This was
                                the phrase commonly employed in acknowledging the numerous letters
                                from American citizens and organizations alleging inhumane or
                                wantonly destructive acts on the part of belligerent forces and
                                calling upon the Government to take some action in regard to
                                them.</note>
                        </p>
                        <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName corresp="#p_WMM1">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Manton M. Wyvell</hi></persName>)</signed>
                            <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Private Secretary</hi>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>